WEBVTT

1
00:00:49.920 --> 00:00:53.160
<i>(BABY CRYING)</i>

2
00:01:05.160 --> 00:01:07.840
This is Mr Mathison. He's a doctor.

3
00:01:09.400 --> 00:01:10.920
Are you okay?

4
00:01:11.240 --> 00:01:13.480
SALESWOMAN: An ambulance
is on the way.

5
00:01:13.600 --> 00:01:16.280
-DR MATHISON: Thank you.
-Okay.

6
00:01:21.760 --> 00:01:23.640
Is there a name yet?

7
00:01:24.960 --> 00:01:26.200
Elijah.

8
00:01:26.280 --> 00:01:29.920
(BABY CONTINUES CRYING)

9
00:01:31.440 --> 00:01:34.160
Is he supposed to be crying like this?

10
00:01:34.680 --> 00:01:35.880
DR MATHISON: May I?

11
00:01:37.480 --> 00:01:38.680
Okay.

12
00:01:41.880 --> 00:01:43.280
(SHUSHING)

13
00:01:51.960 --> 00:01:53.760
Can I have him back?

14
00:01:58.760 --> 00:02:00.920
What happened during the delivery?

15
00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:03.280
Nothing. It was very quick.

16
00:02:03.880 --> 00:02:07.960
The baby just wanted to come right out.
There were no problems.

17
00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:11.720
Did you drop him?

18
00:02:12.600 --> 00:02:13.760
SALESWOMAN: What?

19
00:02:14.560 --> 00:02:16.560
Did you drop this baby?

20
00:02:16.880 --> 00:02:18.640
Jesus Christ. no.

21
00:02:24.080 --> 00:02:26.960
Inform the ambulance
that we have a situation.

22
00:02:27.080 --> 00:02:28.560
SALESWOMAN: Um. Nellie...

23
00:02:30.080 --> 00:02:32.880
I've never seen this.

24
00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:39.880
It appears that your baby
has sustained some fractures

25
00:02:39.960 --> 00:02:42.040
while inside your uterus.

26
00:02:45.520 --> 00:02:48.040
His arms and his legs are broken.

27
00:03:37.680 --> 00:03:41.760
<i>CONDUCTOR: This is Eastrail 177.</i>
<i>Next stop. Philadelphia.</i>

28
00:04:15.920 --> 00:04:17.480
KELLY: Are you alone?

29
00:04:19.600 --> 00:04:20.760
DAVID: Yeah.

30
00:04:20.960 --> 00:04:22.120
Yeah.

31
00:05:07.680 --> 00:05:11.280
Someone left this magazine.
Want to take a look at it?

32
00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:14.440
Could I take a look at that one?

33
00:05:20.480 --> 00:05:21.760
Thanks.

34
00:05:22.480 --> 00:05:24.160
You like sports?

35
00:05:24.360 --> 00:05:27.800
It's my field. I represent athletes.
I'm an agent.

36
00:05:29.440 --> 00:05:32.880
Are you looking for
any male synchronised swimmers?

37
00:05:32.960 --> 00:05:34.680
I'm thinking about getting into that.

38
00:05:34.760 --> 00:05:36.280
(CHUCKLING) Is that right?

39
00:05:38.960 --> 00:05:42.200
I'm afraid of water.
Think that's a problem?

40
00:05:50.640 --> 00:05:53.400
You represent someone
in Philadelphia?

41
00:05:53.680 --> 00:05:56.000
I'm meeting this player
from Temple University.

42
00:05:56.080 --> 00:06:01.840
He's a cornerback.
This kid is 6'1". 210 pounds.

43
00:06:01.960 --> 00:06:05.280
He runs a 40 in 4.3 seconds.
He's gonna be a god.

44
00:06:06.200 --> 00:06:08.080
Do you like football?

45
00:06:09.320 --> 00:06:10.760
Not really.

46
00:06:22.800 --> 00:06:24.440
I'm David Dunn.

47
00:06:25.200 --> 00:06:26.240
Kelly.

48
00:06:26.360 --> 00:06:28.520
-Hi.
-Hi. nice to meet you.

49
00:06:29.080 --> 00:06:30.840
Nice to meet you.

50
00:06:38.760 --> 00:06:41.680
How long are you gonna be
in Philadelphia?

51
00:06:49.440 --> 00:06:50.920
I'm married.

52
00:06:51.320 --> 00:06:52.520
Great.

53
00:06:52.640 --> 00:06:54.000
I'm sorry.

54
00:06:54.160 --> 00:06:56.320
What are you talking about?

55
00:07:00.560 --> 00:07:03.640
I think you misunderstood.
When I was...

56
00:07:04.880 --> 00:07:05.920
-No.
-...saying...

57
00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:07.280
I know.

58
00:07:09.760 --> 00:07:12.400
I think I'm gonna find another seat.

59
00:07:13.320 --> 00:07:15.200
I didn't mean to...

60
00:08:48.200 --> 00:08:50.280
<i>(SINGING ON TV)</i>

61
00:08:54.200 --> 00:08:57.560
<i>WOMAN ON TV: That's what he failed</i>
<i>to realise. I look classy. not trashy.</i>

62
00:08:57.680 --> 00:09:01.760
<i>I look classy. too.</i>
<i>What about me? Don't I look classy?</i>

63
00:09:02.720 --> 00:09:06.400
<i>But I'm afraid you forgot this</i>
<i>and this and...</i>

64
00:09:06.520 --> 00:09:08.760
<i>MAN 1:</i>
<i>Where is you be. banana?</i>

65
00:09:09.440 --> 00:09:11.120
<i>MAN 2: Now I've got you. Weasel.</i>

66
00:09:11.840 --> 00:09:16.040
<i>REPORTER 1: Some cars are still</i>
<i>on fire and the debris is everywhere.</i>

67
00:09:16.560 --> 00:09:17.960
<i>We are not sure at this time</i>

68
00:09:18.040 --> 00:09:20.920
<i>how rescue personnel</i>
<i>will be able to get on scene at all.</i>

69
00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:23.760
<i>REPORTER 2: If you're just tuning in.</i>
<i>Eastrail train number 177</i>

70
00:09:23.840 --> 00:09:26.200
<i>has derailed just outside Philadelphia</i>

71
00:09:26.280 --> 00:09:28.760
<i>and we're bringing you live coverage</i>
<i>from Skycam 4.</i>

72
00:09:28.880 --> 00:09:30.920
<i>REPORTER 1: Yes. that is...</i>
<i>Appears to be a rescue ambulance.</i>

73
00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:34.080
<i>and there are more behind it</i>
<i>I can see on the access road.</i>

74
00:09:34.160 --> 00:09:36.480
<i>I don't know how close</i>
<i>they're gonna be able to get. David.</i>

75
00:09:36.560 --> 00:09:39.040
<i>These are woods and trees.</i>

76
00:09:39.200 --> 00:09:42.480
<i>It's gonna be</i>
<i>a very difficult rescue effort.</i>

77
00:09:50.440 --> 00:09:52.520
(MONITOR BEEPING)

78
00:09:58.040 --> 00:10:00.440
DOCTOR: Try to pack some of that off...

79
00:10:00.840 --> 00:10:02.000
MAN: Yeah.

80
00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:14.080
Hi.

81
00:10:14.560 --> 00:10:16.160
I'm Dr Dubin.

82
00:10:16.800 --> 00:10:20.560
You're in the emergency room
in the Philadelphia City Hospital.

83
00:10:20.640 --> 00:10:23.040
You were in a serious accident.

84
00:10:23.840 --> 00:10:25.280
Look at me.

85
00:10:26.080 --> 00:10:27.920
How are you feeling?

86
00:10:29.840 --> 00:10:31.040
Okay.

87
00:10:31.160 --> 00:10:33.920
Good.
I'm gonna ask you some questions.

88
00:10:34.800 --> 00:10:38.400
Have you had any heart
or asthma problems in the past?

89
00:10:38.640 --> 00:10:39.720
No.

90
00:10:40.040 --> 00:10:42.160
Kidney or renal problems?

91
00:10:42.920 --> 00:10:44.000
No.

92
00:10:44.320 --> 00:10:45.880
Any allergies?

93
00:10:47.760 --> 00:10:48.840
No.

94
00:10:54.640 --> 00:10:57.280
Where were you sitting on the train?

95
00:11:00.560 --> 00:11:02.080
Against the window.

96
00:11:02.160 --> 00:11:04.080
In the passenger car?

97
00:11:05.800 --> 00:11:06.960
Yeah.

98
00:11:09.800 --> 00:11:14.160
-Where are the other passengers?
-Was your family travelling with you?

99
00:11:16.160 --> 00:11:17.280
No.

100
00:11:18.360 --> 00:11:20.680
Did you get up from your seat?

101
00:11:26.640 --> 00:11:29.760
Are you certain
you were in the passenger car?

102
00:11:35.040 --> 00:11:36.200
Yes.

103
00:11:44.480 --> 00:11:47.120
Why are you looking at me like that?

104
00:11:47.400 --> 00:11:50.800
Your train derailed.
Some kind of malfunction.

105
00:11:52.360 --> 00:11:57.040
They only found two people alive so far.
You and this man.

106
00:11:59.840 --> 00:12:04.000
<i>DR DUBIN: His skull was cracked open</i>
<i>and most of his left side was crushed.</i>

107
00:12:05.400 --> 00:12:06.760
<i>And. to answer your question.</i>

108
00:12:06.840 --> 00:12:10.480
<i>there are two reasons</i>
<i>why I'm looking at you like this.</i>

109
00:12:10.760 --> 00:12:13.560
<i>One. because it seems</i>
<i>in a few minutes</i>

110
00:12:13.640 --> 00:12:17.840
<i>that you will officially be</i>
<i>the only survivor of this train wreck.</i>

111
00:12:17.960 --> 00:12:22.240
<i>And two. because</i>
<i>you didn't break one bone.</i>

112
00:12:24.320 --> 00:12:26.760
<i>You don't have a scratch on you.</i>

113
00:13:13.600 --> 00:13:14.640
(INAUDIBLE)

114
00:14:12.440 --> 00:14:13.680
David?

115
00:14:17.080 --> 00:14:20.000
What happened? In New York.

116
00:14:22.920 --> 00:14:25.160
I don't think I got the job.

117
00:14:27.120 --> 00:14:29.160
I'm still going...

118
00:14:30.280 --> 00:14:32.280
I'm still moving there.

119
00:14:33.600 --> 00:14:37.600
Just... Just not now.

120
00:14:43.360 --> 00:14:44.800
Good night.

121
00:14:48.560 --> 00:14:49.760
Night.

122
00:15:02.560 --> 00:15:07.440
Sara Elaston. social worker at Broad
and Locust Community Centre.

123
00:15:09.080 --> 00:15:11.040
we pray for your soul.

124
00:15:13.400 --> 00:15:17.440
Kevin Elliot. businessman. father of six.

125
00:15:19.600 --> 00:15:21.520
we pray for your soul.

126
00:15:23.160 --> 00:15:30.320
Glen Stevens. researcher in the area
of leukaemia at Drexel University.

127
00:15:32.600 --> 00:15:34.520
we pray for your soul.

128
00:15:36.440 --> 00:15:42.680
Jennifer Pennyman. third-grade
teacher at Jefferson Elementary.

129
00:15:45.080 --> 00:15:47.000
<i>we pray for your soul.</i>

130
00:16:54.080 --> 00:16:57.240
-Yes?
-Is Noel in. ma'am?

131
00:16:57.320 --> 00:16:59.120
No. sir. He is not.

132
00:17:00.760 --> 00:17:03.120
I read about you in the paper.

133
00:17:05.280 --> 00:17:09.280
I was in an accident once. too.
A horse almost trampled me to death.

134
00:17:09.360 --> 00:17:12.240
-Wow.
-Had him put down.

135
00:17:14.800 --> 00:17:16.520
That's a sad story.

136
00:17:21.280 --> 00:17:24.280
Could you ask Noel something
for me. please?

137
00:17:24.680 --> 00:17:25.960
Proceed.

138
00:17:26.960 --> 00:17:29.120
Would you ask him to check
how many sick days I've taken

139
00:17:29.200 --> 00:17:31.080
since I worked here?

140
00:17:31.280 --> 00:17:34.680
-That the entire message?
-Yes. ma'am.

141
00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:39.440
Thank you.

142
00:17:52.480 --> 00:17:55.280
QUARTERBACK: And go. Hut!

143
00:17:57.000 --> 00:17:58.160
Damn!

144
00:18:18.320 --> 00:18:19.680
DAVID: Hey. Noel.

145
00:18:20.240 --> 00:18:22.600
NOEL: What. you hit your head
on that train?

146
00:18:22.680 --> 00:18:25.120
Get your brain to start working again?

147
00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:27.120
DAVID: What?

148
00:18:27.760 --> 00:18:29.320
Forty dollars.

149
00:18:30.360 --> 00:18:31.440
Forty dollars what?

150
00:18:31.520 --> 00:18:34.640
You're getting a $40-a-week raise.
That's it.

151
00:18:36.320 --> 00:18:39.520
I checked. You were right.
You've never taken a sick day.

152
00:18:39.600 --> 00:18:43.080
Five years. no sick day. I get it.
You want a raise.

153
00:18:43.480 --> 00:18:45.800
Smart way to make your point.

154
00:19:12.120 --> 00:19:15.400
-Is Joseph okay?
-Yeah. He's asleep.

155
00:19:16.480 --> 00:19:17.560
Oh.

156
00:19:18.920 --> 00:19:20.120
Yeah.

157
00:19:21.400 --> 00:19:23.800
I wanted to ask you a question.

158
00:19:24.400 --> 00:19:25.840
It's gonna sound a little strange.

159
00:19:25.920 --> 00:19:29.200
but. uh. just think about it
for a second. okay?

160
00:19:29.840 --> 00:19:31.000
Okay.

161
00:19:32.720 --> 00:19:35.840
When's the last time I was sick?
You remember?

162
00:19:40.480 --> 00:19:42.240
I don't know.

163
00:19:44.400 --> 00:19:46.200
It's been a while.

164
00:19:47.480 --> 00:19:50.440
I haven't been sick this year.
I know that.

165
00:19:51.280 --> 00:19:52.440
Okay.

166
00:19:53.560 --> 00:19:56.000
Do you remember me getting sick?

167
00:20:01.080 --> 00:20:02.920
Not a specific day.

168
00:20:04.320 --> 00:20:06.120
What's this about?

169
00:20:07.920 --> 00:20:11.000
Audrey. do you remember me
ever getting sick?

170
00:20:11.600 --> 00:20:14.400
In the three years
we lived in this house?

171
00:20:14.480 --> 00:20:16.320
In the old apartment?

172
00:20:16.760 --> 00:20:20.160
Before Joseph was born?
Before we ever got married?

173
00:20:24.080 --> 00:20:25.840
I can't remember.

174
00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:30.320
Don't you think that's kind of weird.

175
00:20:30.400 --> 00:20:34.200
not remembering one cold
or a fever or a sore throat?

176
00:20:36.720 --> 00:20:38.920
What do you think it means?

177
00:20:46.400 --> 00:20:49.880
I think it means
probably too tired to remember.

178
00:20:52.560 --> 00:20:53.720
DAVID: Yeah.

179
00:21:31.880 --> 00:21:35.640
No more sitting in this room.
I let it go on long enough.

180
00:21:36.280 --> 00:21:39.480
I'm not going out there any more.
I'm not getting hurt again.

181
00:21:39.560 --> 00:21:41.120
This was the last time. I told you.

182
00:21:41.200 --> 00:21:43.720
You can't do anything about that.

183
00:21:43.960 --> 00:21:46.320
You might fall between this chair
and that television.

184
00:21:46.400 --> 00:21:49.360
If that's what God has planned for you.
that's what's gonna happen.

185
00:21:49.440 --> 00:21:52.360
You can't hide from it sitting in a room.

186
00:21:55.880 --> 00:21:59.720
They call me Mr Glass at school
'cause I break like glass.

187
00:22:04.880 --> 00:22:10.000
You make this decision now.
to be afraid.

188
00:22:11.960 --> 00:22:14.280
and you will never turn back.

189
00:22:15.840 --> 00:22:19.960
Your whole life.
you will always be afraid.

190
00:22:33.600 --> 00:22:35.440
(CRYING SOFTLY)

191
00:22:35.520 --> 00:22:38.080
-I got a present for you.
-Why?

192
00:22:39.680 --> 00:22:41.160
Forget why.

193
00:22:44.280 --> 00:22:46.080
You want it or not?

194
00:22:49.280 --> 00:22:51.200
Well. go get it. then.

195
00:22:51.600 --> 00:22:53.080
Where is it?

196
00:22:54.760 --> 00:22:58.360
On a bench. across the street.

197
00:23:13.440 --> 00:23:15.480
Someone's gonna take it.

198
00:23:17.440 --> 00:23:20.040
Then you better get out there soon.

199
00:24:34.560 --> 00:24:36.600
I bought a whole bunch.

200
00:24:41.200 --> 00:24:46.120
There'll be one of these waiting for you
every time you want to come out here.

201
00:24:52.160 --> 00:24:55.000
They say this one has
a surprise ending.

202
00:25:04.160 --> 00:25:07.040
ELIJAH: This is
from Fritz Campion's own library.

203
00:25:07.240 --> 00:25:09.160
This is before the first issue
of the comic book

204
00:25:09.240 --> 00:25:11.680
hit the stands in 1968.

205
00:25:12.320 --> 00:25:15.440
It's a classic depiction
of good versus evil.

206
00:25:16.400 --> 00:25:20.360
Notice the square jaw of Slayer.
common in most comic heroes.

207
00:25:20.480 --> 00:25:24.280
And the slightly disproportionate size
of Jaguaro's head to his body.

208
00:25:24.360 --> 00:25:27.360
This again is common.
but only in villains.

209
00:25:28.520 --> 00:25:30.880
The thing to notice about this piece.

210
00:25:30.960 --> 00:25:33.920
the thing that makes it
very. very special.

211
00:25:35.120 --> 00:25:38.080
is its realistic depiction of its figures.

212
00:25:38.280 --> 00:25:40.360
When the characters
reached the magazine.

213
00:25:40.440 --> 00:25:43.800
they were exaggerated.
as always happens.

214
00:25:44.640 --> 00:25:48.160
But this is a vintage.

215
00:25:51.520 --> 00:25:52.800
Well...

216
00:25:58.640 --> 00:26:00.080
Wrap it up.

217
00:26:01.200 --> 00:26:04.080
You've made
a considerably wise decision.

218
00:26:09.200 --> 00:26:11.880
You know. my kid's gonna go berserk.

219
00:26:14.600 --> 00:26:16.440
Once again. please?

220
00:26:16.720 --> 00:26:19.320
My son Jeb. It's a gift for him.

221
00:26:19.600 --> 00:26:21.240
How old is Jeb?

222
00:26:21.840 --> 00:26:23.200
He's four.

223
00:26:25.520 --> 00:26:26.560
No.

224
00:26:27.720 --> 00:26:31.280
No. no. no. no. no.

225
00:26:32.840 --> 00:26:34.680
You need to go. Now.

226
00:26:37.120 --> 00:26:38.680
What'd I say?

227
00:26:39.320 --> 00:26:41.880
Do you see any Teletubbies in here?

228
00:26:42.720 --> 00:26:44.840
Do you see a slender plastic tag
clipped to my shirt

229
00:26:44.920 --> 00:26:47.040
with my name printed on it?

230
00:26:47.120 --> 00:26:50.080
Did you see a little Asian child
with a blank expression sitting outside

231
00:26:50.160 --> 00:26:53.880
in a mechanical helicopter that shakes
when you put quarters in it?

232
00:26:53.960 --> 00:26:57.360
No? Well. that's what you see
at a toy store.

233
00:26:57.800 --> 00:26:59.280
And you must think you're in a toy store

234
00:26:59.360 --> 00:27:02.880
because you're here shopping
for an infant named Jeb.

235
00:27:03.400 --> 00:27:06.240
Now. one of us has made a gross error

236
00:27:06.320 --> 00:27:09.320
and wasted the other person's
valuable time.

237
00:27:09.800 --> 00:27:14.640
This is an art gallery. my friend.
And this is a piece of art.

238
00:27:31.040 --> 00:27:33.160
ELIJAH: We're by appointment only.

239
00:27:34.800 --> 00:27:36.600
DAVID: I got a card from this store.

240
00:27:36.680 --> 00:27:38.400
ELIJAH: Congratulations.
you have a mailbox.

241
00:27:38.480 --> 00:27:41.200
The exhibition isn't for two weeks.

242
00:27:41.280 --> 00:27:44.680
DAVID: This one was under
the windshield wiper of my car.

243
00:27:47.360 --> 00:27:50.000
ELIJAH: How certain are you
that you've never taken ill?

244
00:27:50.080 --> 00:27:52.000
Seventy-five percent.

245
00:27:52.880 --> 00:27:55.880
Well. that's not certain at all. is it?

246
00:27:57.680 --> 00:27:59.720
That's hole number one.

247
00:28:00.720 --> 00:28:03.680
I'm going to be extremely sceptical
about all this.

248
00:28:03.760 --> 00:28:05.400
DAVID: About all what?

249
00:28:07.440 --> 00:28:08.800
I'm assuming
you've never been injured.

250
00:28:08.880 --> 00:28:10.680
Would I be wrong in that assumption?

251
00:28:10.760 --> 00:28:12.600
JOSEPH: Dad's been injured.

252
00:28:14.080 --> 00:28:15.960
Is the child correct?

253
00:28:17.160 --> 00:28:18.520
Yes. sir.

254
00:28:19.080 --> 00:28:22.720
-In college. I was in a car accident.
-Was it serious?

255
00:28:22.800 --> 00:28:25.320
He couldn't play football any more.

256
00:28:26.280 --> 00:28:28.280
That's hole number two.

257
00:28:29.960 --> 00:28:31.680
That's a big one.

258
00:28:35.720 --> 00:28:39.600
Mr Price. can we talk about the note
that you left on my car?

259
00:28:39.680 --> 00:28:42.680
I've studied
the form of comics intimately.

260
00:28:43.040 --> 00:28:48.160
I've spent a third of my life in a hospital
bed with nothing else to do but read.

261
00:28:48.480 --> 00:28:53.240
I believe comics are our last link to
an ancient way of passing on history.

262
00:28:54.320 --> 00:28:56.440
The Egyptians drew on the walls.

263
00:28:56.520 --> 00:29:00.880
Countries all over the world still pass
on knowledge through pictorial forms.

264
00:29:00.960 --> 00:29:03.160
I believe comics are a form of history

265
00:29:03.240 --> 00:29:06.240
that someone somewhere
felt or experienced.

266
00:29:06.840 --> 00:29:09.160
Then. of course. those experiences
and that history

267
00:29:09.240 --> 00:29:10.920
got chewed up
in the commercial machine.

268
00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:14.960
got jazzed up. made titillating.
cartooned for the sale rack.

269
00:29:16.640 --> 00:29:19.560
This city has seen
its share of disasters.

270
00:29:20.160 --> 00:29:22.640
I watched the aftermath
of that plane crash.

271
00:29:22.720 --> 00:29:25.240
I watched the carnage of the hotel fire.

272
00:29:25.320 --> 00:29:29.920
I watched the news. waiting to hear
a very specific combination of words.

273
00:29:30.240 --> 00:29:32.120
but they never came.

274
00:29:32.960 --> 00:29:36.560
Then one day I saw a news story
about a train accident.

275
00:29:36.640 --> 00:29:38.360
and I heard them.

276
00:29:38.880 --> 00:29:43.640
"There is a sole survivor
and he is miraculously unharmed."

277
00:29:47.200 --> 00:29:50.440
I have something
called Osteogenesis Imperfecta.

278
00:29:50.760 --> 00:29:52.840
It's a genetic disorder.

279
00:29:52.920 --> 00:29:54.800
I don't make a particular protein
very well

280
00:29:54.880 --> 00:29:58.880
and it makes my bones very low
in density. very easy to break.

281
00:29:59.920 --> 00:30:02.480
I've had 54 breaks in my life.

282
00:30:02.560 --> 00:30:06.360
and I have the tamest version
of this disorder. type one.

283
00:30:07.440 --> 00:30:10.360
There are type two.
type three. type four.

284
00:30:11.320 --> 00:30:13.720
Type fours don't last very long.

285
00:30:14.880 --> 00:30:17.600
So that's how it popped into my head.

286
00:30:18.240 --> 00:30:23.080
If there is someone like me in the world.
and I'm at one end of the spectrum.

287
00:30:23.160 --> 00:30:27.440
couldn't there be someone else
the opposite of me at the other end?

288
00:30:27.520 --> 00:30:32.040
Someone who doesn't get sick.
who doesn't get hurt like the rest of us.

289
00:30:32.120 --> 00:30:34.880
and he probably doesn't even know it.

290
00:30:36.120 --> 00:30:39.680
The kind of person
these stories are about.

291
00:30:41.280 --> 00:30:45.120
A person put here
to protect the rest of us.

292
00:30:46.400 --> 00:30:47.880
to guard us.

293
00:30:50.800 --> 00:30:54.920
-You think my dad's a real...
-I don't think anything right now.

294
00:30:55.640 --> 00:30:59.520
It's a possibility. One with many holes.

295
00:31:03.680 --> 00:31:06.800
Joseph. don't take another sip
of that water.

296
00:31:09.560 --> 00:31:11.680
-Go throw it in the trash.
-But. Dad...

297
00:31:11.760 --> 00:31:13.480
Do it now. please.

298
00:31:23.240 --> 00:31:26.320
DAVID: I see guys like you all the time
in my work.

299
00:31:27.200 --> 00:31:30.440
You find someone you want
to take advantage of.

300
00:31:30.720 --> 00:31:33.120
You tell them a fantastic story.

301
00:31:34.200 --> 00:31:37.080
Somewhere in there you say.

302
00:31:37.160 --> 00:31:41.520
"I just need your credit card number.
a small down payment."

303
00:31:44.880 --> 00:31:47.080
This morning was the first morning
that I can remember

304
00:31:47.160 --> 00:31:52.720
that I didn't open my eyes
and feel sadness.

305
00:31:54.120 --> 00:31:55.480
(DAVID CHUCKLES)

306
00:31:57.600 --> 00:32:01.680
I thought the person that wrote that note
had an answer for me.

307
00:32:07.680 --> 00:32:12.520
I'm gonna leave now.
Good luck with your exhibition.

308
00:32:12.880 --> 00:32:15.480
So. what kind of job
do you have. David?

309
00:32:15.560 --> 00:32:17.480
You said you've met guys like me
in your work.

310
00:32:17.560 --> 00:32:19.440
What exactly is it that you do?

311
00:32:19.520 --> 00:32:23.240
I work at the university stadium.
I'm a security guard.

312
00:34:28.000 --> 00:34:29.080
(KNOCKING AT DOOR)

313
00:34:40.440 --> 00:34:41.600
Hi.

314
00:34:42.800 --> 00:34:44.840
I've come to a decision.

315
00:34:45.840 --> 00:34:47.000
Okay.

316
00:34:48.200 --> 00:34:52.680
I just want to ask you something. okay?
And you can be totally honest.

317
00:34:54.520 --> 00:34:57.920
I'm prepared for any answer
and it won't affect me.

318
00:35:00.680 --> 00:35:02.800
Have you been with anyone?

319
00:35:03.520 --> 00:35:05.760
I mean.
since we've been having problems.

320
00:35:05.840 --> 00:35:08.040
The answer won't affect me.

321
00:35:11.080 --> 00:35:15.560
I just need to know. You know?
It won't affect me either way.

322
00:35:18.120 --> 00:35:19.240
No.

323
00:35:28.120 --> 00:35:30.000
(CRYING) Sorry. David. Sorry.

324
00:35:35.720 --> 00:35:39.040
Anyway. my decision is

325
00:35:43.280 --> 00:35:45.480
that I want to start again.

326
00:35:48.960 --> 00:35:52.320
That I want it to be like it was
in the beginning.

327
00:35:55.080 --> 00:35:58.560
And it's a big deal
that you walked away from that train.

328
00:36:01.320 --> 00:36:03.840
I feel like it's a second chance.

329
00:36:09.640 --> 00:36:13.720
And if you feel like asking me out
sometime. it'd be okay.

330
00:36:17.160 --> 00:36:18.240
Okay.

331
00:36:32.000 --> 00:36:33.040
<i>JENKINS ON RADIO: Dunn.</i>

332
00:36:33.400 --> 00:36:34.640
Go for Dunn.

333
00:36:34.720 --> 00:36:38.800
<i>It's Jenkins. Look. we got a guy over</i>
<i>at Gate 17C with a bogus ticket.</i>

334
00:36:38.880 --> 00:36:42.600
<i>Says he knows you.</i>
<i>He won't tell me his name.</i>

335
00:36:43.080 --> 00:36:44.880
What's he look like?

336
00:36:45.600 --> 00:36:48.200
ELIJAH: Why is it. do you think.
that of all the professions in the world

337
00:36:48.280 --> 00:36:50.120
you chose protection?

338
00:36:52.400 --> 00:36:54.080
DAVID: You are a very strange man.

339
00:36:54.160 --> 00:36:55.200
ELIJAH: You could've been
a tax accountant.

340
00:36:55.280 --> 00:36:56.400
You could've owned your own gym.

341
00:36:56.480 --> 00:36:58.040
You could've opened
a chain of restaurants.

342
00:36:58.120 --> 00:37:00.640
You could've done
one of 10.000 things

343
00:37:00.720 --> 00:37:03.800
but in the end.
you chose to protect people.

344
00:37:04.960 --> 00:37:08.960
You made that decision
and I find that very. very interesting.

345
00:37:10.760 --> 00:37:13.600
Now all I need is
your credit card number.

346
00:37:14.800 --> 00:37:16.720
That last part was a joke.

347
00:37:18.000 --> 00:37:19.040
(DAVID LAUGHS)

348
00:37:20.800 --> 00:37:23.000
DAVID: You're a big sports fan. are you?

349
00:37:23.080 --> 00:37:25.280
ELIJAH: It's starting to intrigue me.

350
00:37:26.800 --> 00:37:29.840
It gets heaviest 10 minutes
before kickoff.

351
00:37:51.640 --> 00:37:53.480
-Rich. why don't we pat down?
-Right.

352
00:37:53.560 --> 00:37:55.920
-Just give me a minute.
-Is there a problem?

353
00:37:56.000 --> 00:37:58.600
RICH: I'm sorry. I'm gonna have to
search you. Nothing personal.

354
00:37:58.680 --> 00:38:00.640
The tall guy in the camouflage jacket.

355
00:38:00.960 --> 00:38:05.400
Sometimes people carry weapons
in here and they drink too much.

356
00:38:05.880 --> 00:38:09.320
If the team's not doing good.
bad things can happen.

357
00:38:10.760 --> 00:38:14.880
We do pat-downs of the crowd
to discourage people from carrying.

358
00:38:15.240 --> 00:38:17.760
If he's carrying. he'll step out of line.

359
00:38:17.840 --> 00:38:21.000
RICH: Good evening. ma'am.
Put your arms up. please.

360
00:38:31.160 --> 00:38:35.520
Yeah. step right up here for me.
Now can you hold your arms up for me?

361
00:38:42.120 --> 00:38:43.400
DAVID: Okay.

362
00:38:44.240 --> 00:38:47.200
I got you a seat
up in the yellow section.

363
00:38:47.280 --> 00:38:51.160
It's in the nosebleeds.
but at least you won't get spit on.

364
00:38:51.960 --> 00:38:53.080
DAVID: All right.

365
00:38:53.160 --> 00:38:56.880
How'd you know that guy you bumped
was carrying a weapon?

366
00:38:58.720 --> 00:39:00.280
I don't know.

367
00:39:00.880 --> 00:39:04.120
Maybe it was that camouflage
army jacket he was wearing.

368
00:39:05.440 --> 00:39:08.240
Those guys like to carry hunting knives
and stuff for show.

369
00:39:08.320 --> 00:39:10.840
You thought he was carrying a knife?

370
00:39:11.800 --> 00:39:13.360
I thought
he was carrying something. yeah.

371
00:39:13.440 --> 00:39:14.960
But not a knife.

372
00:39:18.480 --> 00:39:24.400
I got a...picture of a silver gun
with a black grip tucked in his pants.

373
00:39:25.880 --> 00:39:27.880
You know. like on TV.

374
00:39:29.680 --> 00:39:32.640
You have good instincts
for things like that?

375
00:39:32.720 --> 00:39:33.760
Like what?

376
00:39:33.840 --> 00:39:37.040
Knowing when people
have done something wrong.

377
00:39:39.520 --> 00:39:43.360
-Yeah.
-Have you ever tried to develop it?

378
00:39:44.720 --> 00:39:47.400
-I don't know what you're asking me.
-Your skill.

379
00:39:48.760 --> 00:39:51.200
Look. I gotta be down on the sidelines
during the game.

380
00:39:51.280 --> 00:39:52.480
You can get to your seat
right down here.

381
00:39:52.560 --> 00:39:55.800
The characters in comics
are often attributed special powers.

382
00:39:55.880 --> 00:39:59.160
Invisibility. x-ray vision.
things of that sort.

383
00:40:00.520 --> 00:40:01.560
Okay.

384
00:40:03.200 --> 00:40:04.960
I don't want to play this game any more.

385
00:40:05.040 --> 00:40:07.560
It's an exaggeration of the truth.

386
00:40:07.960 --> 00:40:11.440
Maybe it's based on something
as simple as instinct.

387
00:40:13.240 --> 00:40:14.920
But he might not have been
carrying anything.

388
00:40:15.000 --> 00:40:17.600
But he might have been carrying
a silver gun with a black grip

389
00:40:17.680 --> 00:40:20.000
-tucked in his pants.
<i>-JENKINS ON RADIO: Dunn.</i>

390
00:40:20.760 --> 00:40:22.040
I gotta go.

391
00:40:24.120 --> 00:40:26.400
Yeah. I know. I'll be right down.

392
00:40:26.480 --> 00:40:29.320
-One last question.
-What?

393
00:40:29.760 --> 00:40:33.360
That car accident you were in.
Was there anyone else involved?

394
00:40:36.440 --> 00:40:37.560
Yeah.

395
00:40:38.240 --> 00:40:41.520
My wife Audrey.
She was in the car with me.

396
00:40:43.960 --> 00:40:46.120
Have a good life. Elijah.

397
00:40:46.920 --> 00:40:50.600
Next time. try to buy your tickets
at an authorised sales location.

398
00:40:50.720 --> 00:40:51.920
<i>(JENKINS CHATTERING ON RADIO)</i>

399
00:40:53.280 --> 00:40:54.440
I'm on my way.

400
00:40:58.560 --> 00:41:00.880
<i>ANNOUNCER ON RADIO:</i>
<i>...into the investigation of Train 177</i>

401
00:41:00.960 --> 00:41:04.160
<i>being conducted</i>
<i>at the Eastrail holding warehouses.</i>

402
00:41:04.240 --> 00:41:06.600
<i>The city council has stepped up</i>
<i>plans to pass a bill</i>

403
00:41:06.680 --> 00:41:10.080
<i>requiring higher standards</i>
<i>for inspection and maintenance</i>

404
00:41:10.160 --> 00:41:14.640
<i>of all rail transportation in Philadelphia</i>
<i>and its outlying districts.</i>

405
00:41:22.720 --> 00:41:24.440
Hold up a second!

406
00:42:19.400 --> 00:42:21.920
I just want to ask you something!

407
00:42:50.520 --> 00:42:52.600
(ELIJAH SCREAMING)

408
00:42:56.640 --> 00:42:58.360
(CRYING)

409
00:43:31.840 --> 00:43:34.120
JOSEPH: Dad! Hey. Dad!

410
00:43:41.520 --> 00:43:42.800
Dad!

411
00:43:54.480 --> 00:43:55.880
Joseph. do you know
how mad your mother would be

412
00:43:55.960 --> 00:43:58.120
if she knew you were playing football?

413
00:43:58.240 --> 00:44:00.040
Are you gonna tell?

414
00:44:01.240 --> 00:44:04.600
You want to play last of the downs?
We got a big guy like you.

415
00:44:04.680 --> 00:44:08.080
You could play on opposite sides.
He's Potter's cousin.

416
00:44:08.960 --> 00:44:11.520
He's starting cornerback
at Temple University.

417
00:44:11.600 --> 00:44:13.600
He's going pro in the draft.

418
00:44:13.680 --> 00:44:16.640
They say he can run the 40
in 4.3 seconds.

419
00:44:17.240 --> 00:44:18.800
DAVID: I've heard.

420
00:44:19.240 --> 00:44:22.160
You can beat him. Dad. Let's beat 'em.

421
00:44:22.240 --> 00:44:23.840
I'm gonna go in.

422
00:44:23.920 --> 00:44:26.440
Just play one set of downs.
I told them you were great.

423
00:44:26.560 --> 00:44:28.640
-Why'd you do that?
-Just one!

424
00:44:28.720 --> 00:44:30.800
I'm gonna go in.
I've got some things to do.

425
00:44:30.880 --> 00:44:33.680
-What things?
-I'm gonna work out.

426
00:44:33.760 --> 00:44:35.440
-I'll help you.
-No. I don't need...

427
00:44:35.520 --> 00:44:36.720
-I can't play. guys!
-There's nothing to...

428
00:44:36.800 --> 00:44:39.000
I'm working out with my dad!

429
00:44:39.200 --> 00:44:42.360
POTTER'S COUSIN: Three-four.
Go. go. Go. Here we go. Ready.

430
00:44:42.440 --> 00:44:45.800
Hut! Doing good. Right there! There!

431
00:45:00.560 --> 00:45:02.720
How much did you put on there?

432
00:45:11.600 --> 00:45:15.080
You put too much. That's 250 pounds.

433
00:45:15.600 --> 00:45:17.560
How much can you lift?

434
00:45:19.160 --> 00:45:21.600
That's the most I ever lifted.

435
00:45:23.800 --> 00:45:26.520
That could've been dangerous. Joseph.

436
00:45:26.760 --> 00:45:28.680
Why don't you go upstairs now
and let me finish up. okay?

437
00:45:28.760 --> 00:45:31.600
I'll take it off. I'll help you right.

438
00:45:36.480 --> 00:45:39.520
You think you could've beaten up
Bruce Lee?

439
00:45:40.200 --> 00:45:41.400
No.

440
00:45:42.160 --> 00:45:44.240
I mean. if you knew karate.

441
00:45:44.640 --> 00:45:45.920
Nope.

442
00:45:50.720 --> 00:45:53.880
What if he wasn't allowed to kick
and you were really mad at him?

443
00:45:53.960 --> 00:45:55.320
No. Joseph.

444
00:46:37.240 --> 00:46:39.360
How much did you take off?

445
00:46:41.880 --> 00:46:43.280
I lied.

446
00:46:47.080 --> 00:46:48.560
You added?

447
00:46:57.120 --> 00:46:58.640
How much is it?

448
00:47:00.360 --> 00:47:01.920
270 pounds.

449
00:47:05.840 --> 00:47:07.280
Let's put more.

450
00:47:11.120 --> 00:47:12.320
Okay.

451
00:47:16.720 --> 00:47:20.400
Why don't you move back a little.
just to be safe. okay?

452
00:47:24.680 --> 00:47:26.560
(GROANING)

453
00:47:32.880 --> 00:47:34.280
(GRUNTS)

454
00:47:46.800 --> 00:47:48.000
(CLATTERING)

455
00:47:52.320 --> 00:47:53.680
More?

456
00:48:05.760 --> 00:48:09.760
You should never do anything like this.
You know that. right?

457
00:48:11.280 --> 00:48:13.680
What do you do
if something bad happens?

458
00:48:13.760 --> 00:48:15.200
Get Mom.

459
00:48:16.280 --> 00:48:17.320
Right.

460
00:48:24.520 --> 00:48:25.920
(GRUNTS)

461
00:48:49.680 --> 00:48:51.400
(PANTING)

462
00:48:53.360 --> 00:48:55.920
How much did you put on that time?

463
00:49:00.120 --> 00:49:01.640
All of it.

464
00:49:03.800 --> 00:49:06.000
What else can we use?

465
00:49:09.760 --> 00:49:11.520
(DAVID GRUNTING)

466
00:49:32.360 --> 00:49:34.160
How much is it?

467
00:49:43.320 --> 00:49:45.240
How much is it. Dad?

468
00:49:48.280 --> 00:49:51.000
About 350 pounds.

469
00:49:58.200 --> 00:50:00.040
DOCTOR: Fracture of
the fifth metacarpal of the right hand.

470
00:50:00.120 --> 00:50:03.440
as well as multiple fractures
of the sixth. seventh and eighth ribs.

471
00:50:03.560 --> 00:50:06.200
The worst of the injury. however.
was sustained to the right leg

472
00:50:06.280 --> 00:50:08.160
in the form of a spiral fracture.

473
00:50:08.240 --> 00:50:11.520
There were 14 breaks.
It simply shattered.

474
00:50:13.360 --> 00:50:15.360
They call me Mr Glass.

475
00:50:15.960 --> 00:50:18.400
-DOCTOR: Who does?
-Kids.

476
00:50:19.760 --> 00:50:23.520
DOCTOR: Are you all right. Mr Price?
Shall I continue?

477
00:50:25.280 --> 00:50:27.560
Pins were placed
throughout the length of the leg.

478
00:50:27.640 --> 00:50:30.400
The use of a wheelchair will be needed
for a two-month period.

479
00:50:30.480 --> 00:50:34.000
The use of crutches will follow
for 12 to 14 months.

480
00:50:34.080 --> 00:50:36.240
Hospital stay will range
from five to eight days.

481
00:50:36.320 --> 00:50:39.040
followed by nine to 12 months
of physical therapy.

482
00:50:39.160 --> 00:50:40.760
Prescribed medication
for pain management

483
00:50:40.840 --> 00:50:45.040
will take the usual forms
of morphine drip. Percocet. Darvocet.

484
00:50:56.360 --> 00:50:58.160
Your 10:00 is here.

485
00:50:58.360 --> 00:51:01.280
The hospital discharged him
this morning.

486
00:51:02.000 --> 00:51:03.680
Okay. Thanks.

487
00:51:13.240 --> 00:51:14.800
Elijah. right?

488
00:51:15.200 --> 00:51:17.160
We're gonna prevent
any substantial atrophy

489
00:51:17.240 --> 00:51:21.160
of your good leg with this.
and it works your quadriceps.

490
00:51:22.280 --> 00:51:24.640
ELIJAH: How long
have you been married?

491
00:51:27.200 --> 00:51:30.440
-Twelve years.
-How'd you get together?

492
00:51:30.520 --> 00:51:31.880
(AUDREY LAUGHS)

493
00:51:32.520 --> 00:51:34.320
I'm a little nervous being here.

494
00:51:34.400 --> 00:51:37.360
I ask too many questions
when I'm nervous.

495
00:51:40.240 --> 00:51:41.840
AUDREY: A car accident.

496
00:51:43.280 --> 00:51:46.200
Now you're gonna have to tell me more.

497
00:51:50.320 --> 00:51:52.760
My husband was a star athlete
in college

498
00:51:52.880 --> 00:51:55.560
and we were in an accident together.

499
00:51:56.560 --> 00:51:58.720
Our car flipped on an icy road
and we were both injured

500
00:51:58.800 --> 00:52:00.480
and he couldn't play football any more.

501
00:52:00.640 --> 00:52:03.360
And if that hadn't happened. we
probably wouldn't have been together.

502
00:52:03.440 --> 00:52:04.800
How so?

503
00:52:05.280 --> 00:52:07.160
I think we should talk about your rehab.

504
00:52:07.240 --> 00:52:10.160
You don't have to answer
if you don't want to.

505
00:52:10.720 --> 00:52:13.480
So. tell me more
about the quad machine.

506
00:52:15.640 --> 00:52:17.840
It prevents atrophy by...

507
00:52:20.280 --> 00:52:22.520
I couldn't spend my life with someone
who played football.

508
00:52:22.600 --> 00:52:24.880
It's pretty much that simple.

509
00:52:25.720 --> 00:52:27.320
I mean. I don't hate the game.

510
00:52:27.400 --> 00:52:30.280
I admire the amount of skill it involves
and like everyone else.

511
00:52:30.360 --> 00:52:32.720
I was in awe of the way he played it.

512
00:52:32.800 --> 00:52:36.360
But football in many ways is
the opposite of what I do.

513
00:52:37.400 --> 00:52:39.960
You're rewarded
the more you punish your opponent.

514
00:52:40.040 --> 00:52:44.280
It's too much about violence
and I don't want violence in my life.

515
00:52:44.840 --> 00:52:48.200
It's not a thing many people
can understand. but...

516
00:52:48.480 --> 00:52:51.520
Anyway. fate stepped in
with that car accident

517
00:52:51.600 --> 00:52:53.880
and took football out of the equation.

518
00:52:53.960 --> 00:52:56.920
ELIJAH: And everyone lived
happily ever after.

519
00:52:58.720 --> 00:52:59.760
Sort of.

520
00:53:00.560 --> 00:53:03.320
What part of David's body was injured?

521
00:53:05.320 --> 00:53:07.840
Who said my husband's name
was David?

522
00:53:08.080 --> 00:53:09.760
(CROWD CHEERING)

523
00:54:00.720 --> 00:54:05.560
<i>ELIJAH: A 737 crashes on takeoff.</i>
<i>172 die. No survivors.</i>

524
00:54:06.280 --> 00:54:10.480
A hotel fire downtown. 211 die.
No survivors.

525
00:54:11.120 --> 00:54:14.800
An Eastrail train derails
seven-and-a-half miles outside the city.

526
00:54:14.880 --> 00:54:18.320
131 die. One survivor.

527
00:54:18.960 --> 00:54:20.600
He is unharmed.

528
00:54:21.520 --> 00:54:24.520
I've spoken with your husband
about his survival.

529
00:54:24.600 --> 00:54:27.400
I suggested
a rather unbelievable possibility.

530
00:54:27.480 --> 00:54:32.160
Since then. I've come to believe
that possibility. however unbelievable.

531
00:54:32.760 --> 00:54:34.880
is now more a probability.

532
00:54:35.320 --> 00:54:37.520
And what was it you suggested?

533
00:54:38.360 --> 00:54:43.280
These are mediocre times. Mrs Dunn.
People are starting to lose hope.

534
00:54:43.360 --> 00:54:45.800
It's hard for many to believe
there are extraordinary things

535
00:54:45.880 --> 00:54:48.480
inside themselves as well as others.

536
00:54:49.120 --> 00:54:51.600
I hope you can keep an open mind.

537
00:55:34.000 --> 00:55:37.840
Excuse me. sir?
Can you step out of line. please?

538
00:55:43.080 --> 00:55:44.320
We've been having some problems

539
00:55:44.400 --> 00:55:47.080
with people selling drugs
here in the stadium.

540
00:55:47.200 --> 00:55:49.960
Would you mind
if I check your pockets?

541
00:55:50.680 --> 00:55:52.600
Raise your arms. please.

542
00:55:53.640 --> 00:55:57.160
-Come on. raise 'em up.
-MAN: I just got here.

543
00:56:08.760 --> 00:56:10.920
Can I put my hands down now?

544
00:56:16.280 --> 00:56:17.640
Can I go?

545
00:56:19.520 --> 00:56:20.800
Yeah.

546
00:56:23.040 --> 00:56:24.720
Hope you find them.

547
00:56:34.200 --> 00:56:35.560
<i>JENKINS ON RADIO: Yo. Dunn.</i>

548
00:56:37.280 --> 00:56:38.440
Yeah.

549
00:56:38.520 --> 00:56:41.600
<i>This just came into the office.</i>
<i>Your kid was hurt.</i>

550
00:56:43.000 --> 00:56:44.280
Where is he?

551
00:56:44.360 --> 00:56:48.280
<i>Some play rehearsal at school.</i>
<i>He wants you to come down there.</i>

552
00:57:03.040 --> 00:57:04.760
BOY: Is that your dad?

553
00:57:08.760 --> 00:57:11.400
I bet my dad could beat up your dad.

554
00:57:15.200 --> 00:57:18.160
No. he insisted we call only you.

555
00:57:18.640 --> 00:57:20.520
Though we had some trouble
tracking you down.

556
00:57:20.600 --> 00:57:23.000
I mean. you're not on our list.

557
00:57:23.760 --> 00:57:26.040
-Audrey handles this type of stuff.
-Oh.

558
00:57:26.400 --> 00:57:28.200
What type of stuff?

559
00:57:29.760 --> 00:57:31.320
Joseph stuff.

560
00:57:35.080 --> 00:57:37.440
Do I need to put any smelly ointment
on him or anything?

561
00:57:37.520 --> 00:57:41.920
No. no. It's more emotional damage.
Not too serious. physically.

562
00:57:43.360 --> 00:57:46.440
Nothing like when I sent you
to the hospital.

563
00:57:50.520 --> 00:57:52.120
What was that?

564
00:57:52.960 --> 00:57:56.680
My office was on the other side
of the building back then.

565
00:58:00.200 --> 00:58:02.440
You don't remember me. do you?

566
00:58:04.760 --> 00:58:08.160
-No. ma'am.
-I had red hair.

567
00:58:11.160 --> 00:58:14.920
Well. you were a little younger
than Joseph when it happened.

568
00:58:15.920 --> 00:58:20.600
Did you know that we changed
the rules of conduct around the pool

569
00:58:20.680 --> 00:58:22.240
because of you?

570
00:58:24.800 --> 00:58:29.040
The kids still tell about it
like it was some sort of ghost story.

571
00:58:30.520 --> 00:58:34.480
"Did you know there was
a kid nearly drowned in that pool?

572
00:58:36.160 --> 00:58:39.120
"He lay on the bottom of the pool
for five minutes.

573
00:58:39.200 --> 00:58:42.960
"and when they pulled him out.
he was dead."

574
00:58:48.360 --> 00:58:52.320
We let them tell it.
It helps keep them safe.

575
00:58:55.880 --> 00:58:57.960
You still phobic of water?

576
00:59:01.520 --> 00:59:03.720
<i>JOSEPH: It was Potter</i>
<i>and another guy.</i>

577
00:59:04.800 --> 00:59:08.800
They were messing with
this Chinese girl in the dressing room.

578
00:59:08.880 --> 00:59:12.320
You can't let bad things
happen to good people. right?

579
00:59:13.360 --> 00:59:16.280
That's your code. right?
That's the hero's code?

580
00:59:18.360 --> 00:59:21.400
I tried to make them stop.
but they kept pushing me down

581
00:59:21.480 --> 00:59:24.360
and they wouldn't let me get back up.

582
00:59:27.280 --> 00:59:30.000
I thought maybe 'cause you're my dad.

583
00:59:31.320 --> 00:59:33.760
I thought I might be like you.

584
00:59:37.120 --> 00:59:38.800
I'm not like you.

585
00:59:41.040 --> 00:59:42.560
You are like me.

586
00:59:44.400 --> 00:59:46.200
We can both get hurt.

587
00:59:47.960 --> 00:59:51.240
-I'm just an ordinary man.
-No. you're not.

588
00:59:52.320 --> 00:59:54.600
Why do you keep saying that?

589
01:00:02.760 --> 01:00:06.160
AUDREY: Elijah Price came to visit me
at the centre today.

590
01:00:06.960 --> 01:00:08.200
Jesus.

591
01:00:10.200 --> 01:00:14.960
He didn't do anything. He just...
Told me his theory.

592
01:00:16.240 --> 01:00:20.720
That's sad when patients get like that.
They lose reality.

593
01:00:25.880 --> 01:00:28.480
Joseph. what the hell are you doing?

594
01:00:28.560 --> 01:00:29.920
AUDREY: Oh. my God.

595
01:00:30.680 --> 01:00:34.320
You don't believe. I'll show you.
You can't get hurt.

596
01:00:34.520 --> 01:00:35.880
That gun's not loaded.

597
01:00:35.960 --> 01:00:37.320
He doesn't know
where I keep the bullets.

598
01:00:37.400 --> 01:00:39.880
JOSEPH: In your Rookie
of the Year trophy.

599
01:00:40.520 --> 01:00:42.720
Joseph. did you load that gun?

600
01:00:43.440 --> 01:00:46.680
-You won't get hurt.
-DAVID: Elijah was wrong.

601
01:00:47.160 --> 01:00:49.640
-AUDREY: When did he meet Elijah?
-He was with me when I met him.

602
01:00:49.720 --> 01:00:51.640
JOSEPH: No one believes him.

603
01:00:52.000 --> 01:00:53.840
Joseph. listen to me.

604
01:00:54.960 --> 01:00:59.880
Sometimes when people get sick
or hurt for a long time. like Elijah.

605
01:01:00.200 --> 01:01:02.200
their mind gets hurt. too.

606
01:01:02.440 --> 01:01:04.000
and they start to think things
that aren't true.

607
01:01:04.080 --> 01:01:06.160
He told me what he thought
about your father.

608
01:01:06.240 --> 01:01:07.760
It isn't true.

609
01:01:08.040 --> 01:01:09.600
I'll show you.

610
01:01:12.680 --> 01:01:14.720
Do you remember the story
about the boy

611
01:01:14.800 --> 01:01:16.640
that almost drowned in the pool?

612
01:01:16.720 --> 01:01:18.960
That was me they were talking about.
I almost died.

613
01:01:19.040 --> 01:01:20.840
-You're lying.
-That was me. I'm not lying. okay?

614
01:01:20.920 --> 01:01:22.080
I just didn't remember it. that's all.

615
01:01:22.160 --> 01:01:24.440
Joseph. you know
your father was injured in college.

616
01:01:24.520 --> 01:01:27.360
You know that. You know all about that!

617
01:01:28.560 --> 01:01:30.960
Don't do it. He'll die. Joseph.

618
01:01:31.040 --> 01:01:33.480
-I'll just shoot him once.
-Joseph. listen to what your...

619
01:01:33.560 --> 01:01:34.760
(GUN COCKING)

620
01:01:35.760 --> 01:01:37.520
JOSEPH: Don't be scared.

621
01:01:38.920 --> 01:01:42.800
Joseph. if you pull that trigger.
I'm going to leave.

622
01:01:43.720 --> 01:01:46.960
Do you understand?
I'm going to go to New York.

623
01:01:47.120 --> 01:01:50.120
You're right. If you pull that trigger.

624
01:01:50.200 --> 01:01:54.040
that bullet is just gonna bounce off me
and I'm not going to be hurt.

625
01:01:54.120 --> 01:01:56.400
But then I'm gonna go upstairs
and I'm gonna pack

626
01:01:56.480 --> 01:01:59.080
and I'm going to leave for New York!

627
01:01:59.920 --> 01:02:01.000
-Why?
-Because I thought

628
01:02:01.080 --> 01:02:04.240
we were just starting
to be friends for real.

629
01:02:04.800 --> 01:02:05.920
And friends will listen to each other.

630
01:02:06.000 --> 01:02:09.920
(STAMMERING) And they don't
shoot each other. do they. Audrey?

631
01:02:10.760 --> 01:02:13.080
No shooting friends. Joseph.

632
01:02:13.920 --> 01:02:15.200
DAVID: Joseph!

633
01:02:16.480 --> 01:02:19.360
You are about to be in big trouble!

634
01:02:20.680 --> 01:02:21.840
Now I am your father

635
01:02:21.920 --> 01:02:25.920
and I am telling you to put
that goddamn gun down right now!

636
01:02:26.160 --> 01:02:27.400
One.

637
01:02:28.360 --> 01:02:29.520
two...

638
01:02:47.840 --> 01:02:50.280
<i>ELIJAH: I followed the guy</i>
<i>in the camouflage jacket.</i>

639
01:02:52.400 --> 01:02:56.800
He had a silver gun with a black grip
tucked in the back of his pants.

640
01:02:59.440 --> 01:03:02.560
Were you really injured
in that car accident in college?

641
01:03:02.640 --> 01:03:04.800
'Cause I believe you faked it.

642
01:03:04.880 --> 01:03:07.600
I believe you took the opportunity
to end your football career.

643
01:03:07.720 --> 01:03:09.120
no questions asked.

644
01:03:09.200 --> 01:03:12.600
And I think you did it.
of all things. for a woman.

645
01:03:13.040 --> 01:03:17.680
I guess that makes sense.
Football's what. just 10 years?

646
01:03:18.400 --> 01:03:22.440
But love. now. that's forever.

647
01:03:25.400 --> 01:03:28.640
And that little bit of sadness
in the mornings you spoke of.

648
01:03:28.720 --> 01:03:30.960
I think I know what that is.

649
01:03:31.040 --> 01:03:34.640
Perhaps you're not doing
what you're supposed to be doing.

650
01:03:34.760 --> 01:03:36.400
DAVID: Most guns have
a black or silver handle.

651
01:03:36.480 --> 01:03:38.640
I had a 50-50 shot
of getting the colour right.

652
01:03:38.720 --> 01:03:41.400
-That's not what I witnessed.
-Stop.

653
01:03:42.040 --> 01:03:44.720
Stop messing with my life. Elijah.

654
01:03:45.560 --> 01:03:47.440
My son almost shot me last night

655
01:03:47.520 --> 01:03:49.320
because he wanted to prove
you were right.

656
01:03:49.400 --> 01:03:52.040
I never said you couldn't be killed.
I never said that.

657
01:03:52.120 --> 01:03:55.800
-My wife was right.
-There have been three major disasters

658
01:03:55.880 --> 01:03:58.080
and you were the only one unharmed.

659
01:03:58.160 --> 01:03:59.800
I have been sick.

660
01:04:02.480 --> 01:04:04.760
When I was a kid. I spent a week
in the hospital getting better

661
01:04:04.840 --> 01:04:06.440
from pneumonia.

662
01:04:07.200 --> 01:04:08.960
I almost drowned.

663
01:04:10.040 --> 01:04:12.760
Two skinny little kids were fooling
around in a pool dunking me

664
01:04:12.840 --> 01:04:14.480
and I swallowed some water.

665
01:04:14.560 --> 01:04:17.560
They didn't know it
and it almost killed me.

666
01:04:18.000 --> 01:04:21.840
Heroes don't get killed like that.
Normal people do. right?

667
01:04:24.360 --> 01:04:27.080
I don't need to see you any more. okay?

668
01:04:28.760 --> 01:04:31.120
Please stay away from my family.

669
01:04:40.320 --> 01:04:43.960
<i>(PUNK ROCK MUSIC</i>
<i>PLAYING ON RADIO)</i>

670
01:04:45.280 --> 01:04:47.520
Hey. man. it's 20 after.
It's time to choose.

671
01:04:47.600 --> 01:04:49.200
I gotta head.

672
01:04:53.960 --> 01:04:56.080
You better not be jacking off
to the Japanese comics.

673
01:04:56.160 --> 01:04:57.720
I swear to God.

674
01:05:11.240 --> 01:05:14.200
Look. man.
I didn't know you were in a...

675
01:05:15.800 --> 01:05:18.320
Just choose something. all right?

676
01:05:23.760 --> 01:05:25.640
AUDREY: The babysitter's here.

677
01:05:28.440 --> 01:05:31.520
-Should we cancel?
-I'm fine.

678
01:05:34.680 --> 01:05:36.840
We can do this another time.

679
01:05:37.680 --> 01:05:39.240
Don't lie.

680
01:05:41.560 --> 01:05:43.840
I'm fine. I just got mixed up.

681
01:05:51.680 --> 01:05:54.760
How about we just go
for a couple drinks?

682
01:05:59.960 --> 01:06:03.080
Okay. look. man.
I'm just gonna wheel you out. All right?

683
01:06:03.160 --> 01:06:04.720
You can think about things outside
on the sidewalk.

684
01:06:04.800 --> 01:06:08.560
I gotta get some chicken in me.
you know what I'm saying?

685
01:06:25.320 --> 01:06:26.640
Shit!

686
01:06:43.320 --> 01:06:44.600
Dude.

687
01:06:47.640 --> 01:06:48.880
Man. I don't care if you are
in a wheelchair.

688
01:06:48.960 --> 01:06:51.920
if you do that again. I'm calling 5-0.

689
01:06:54.480 --> 01:06:55.520
Man.

690
01:07:06.640 --> 01:07:11.280
That's it. crackerjack. You're gonna be
sitting your ass in jail now.

691
01:07:32.680 --> 01:07:34.560
How much for this one?

692
01:07:37.640 --> 01:07:39.120
-Rust?
-Yeah.

693
01:07:41.120 --> 01:07:43.280
As a colour. not as rust.

694
01:07:43.560 --> 01:07:47.000
You know.
like rust-coloured paint or wood.

695
01:07:49.160 --> 01:07:51.000
I didn't know that.

696
01:07:52.520 --> 01:07:54.320
Mine's still brown.

697
01:07:55.200 --> 01:07:56.800
Okay. my turn.

698
01:07:57.280 --> 01:07:58.880
Favourite song.

699
01:07:59.800 --> 01:08:03.320
<i>Soft and Wet</i> by
The Artist Formerly Known as Prince.

700
01:08:03.920 --> 01:08:05.200
What?

701
01:08:06.360 --> 01:08:08.680
We're supposed to be honest.

702
01:08:09.240 --> 01:08:10.600
<i>Soft and Wet.</i>

703
01:08:11.880 --> 01:08:13.920
(LAUGHING) That's very interesting.

704
01:08:14.240 --> 01:08:15.880
Okay. my turn.

705
01:08:17.880 --> 01:08:22.320
When was the first time
the thought popped into your head

706
01:08:22.400 --> 01:08:24.360
we might not make it?

707
01:08:25.880 --> 01:08:27.720
That's not the game.

708
01:08:28.040 --> 01:08:31.120
It's a first date. There aren't any rules.

709
01:08:31.200 --> 01:08:32.720
(DAVID SIGHS)

710
01:08:35.440 --> 01:08:38.880
-Don't know for sure.
-Think carefully.

711
01:08:40.200 --> 01:08:43.800
-What about the game?
-It's over. I won.

712
01:08:46.200 --> 01:08:48.040
Look. maybe it wasn't
a specific moment.

713
01:08:48.120 --> 01:08:51.960
-Maybe it was time...
-I had a nightmare one night

714
01:08:55.080 --> 01:08:59.320
and I didn't wake you up
so you could tell me that it was okay.

715
01:09:00.160 --> 01:09:02.560
I think that was the first time.

716
01:09:04.800 --> 01:09:06.480
Does that count?

717
01:09:08.400 --> 01:09:09.920
That counts.

718
01:09:14.200 --> 01:09:17.440
Do you knowingly keep
me and Joseph at a distance?

719
01:09:25.760 --> 01:09:26.960
Yes.

720
01:09:28.280 --> 01:09:29.320
Why?

721
01:09:32.280 --> 01:09:33.840
I don't know.

722
01:09:38.960 --> 01:09:41.440
I just don't feel right. Audrey.

723
01:09:43.120 --> 01:09:46.320
Something's just not right.

724
01:09:49.680 --> 01:09:51.720
Do you resent us. David?

725
01:09:52.880 --> 01:09:55.000
Resent the life you have?

726
01:09:57.240 --> 01:09:59.320
You know. there were a lot
of other things you could've done

727
01:09:59.400 --> 01:10:02.960
after college. These were your choices.

728
01:10:08.160 --> 01:10:10.400
You know. even if it meant
we couldn't have been together.

729
01:10:10.480 --> 01:10:13.440
I never would've wished
that injury on you.

730
01:10:14.000 --> 01:10:17.600
What you could do physically
was a gift.

731
01:10:18.960 --> 01:10:21.680
I never would've wished it to go away.

732
01:10:23.960 --> 01:10:25.800
You know that. right?

733
01:10:30.080 --> 01:10:32.320
You got two calls
after Joseph went to bed.

734
01:10:32.400 --> 01:10:33.840
One came through
while I was on the other line.

735
01:10:33.920 --> 01:10:35.320
but I wasn't talking too long.

736
01:10:35.400 --> 01:10:36.800
There was an emergency
with my sister.

737
01:10:36.920 --> 01:10:38.720
She tried to do her own perm
and now she looks

738
01:10:38.800 --> 01:10:41.440
-like she's stuck her head...
-Who called through?

739
01:10:42.520 --> 01:10:44.520
Someone from New York.

740
01:10:44.640 --> 01:10:47.680
About a security job.
They want to hire you.

741
01:10:47.920 --> 01:10:49.360
I didn't know you guys
were moving to New York.

742
01:10:49.440 --> 01:10:51.400
Thanks for telling me.

743
01:10:51.880 --> 01:10:54.000
We weren't all gonna move.

744
01:10:55.800 --> 01:10:57.120
Oh.

745
01:10:59.680 --> 01:11:02.080
I let the answering machine pick up
the other call.

746
01:11:06.960 --> 01:11:08.000
GIRL: Great.

747
01:11:20.640 --> 01:11:24.520
Look. let's just be honest here.
We're just at the beginning.

748
01:11:24.600 --> 01:11:28.480
and I don't expect you or I to change
the course of where our lives

749
01:11:28.560 --> 01:11:31.080
were headed because of one date.

750
01:11:32.360 --> 01:11:37.080
And if you do go to New York.
we can develop this.

751
01:11:37.160 --> 01:11:39.160
We'll just be forced to take it slow.

752
01:11:40.320 --> 01:11:44.640
And in the end.
I think that's definitely better.

753
01:11:46.640 --> 01:11:48.280
I mean. this is
our second time around. David.

754
01:11:48.360 --> 01:11:50.840
I didn't expect us to get carried away.

755
01:11:53.320 --> 01:11:56.760
Then I guess "congratulations"
is the right thing to say.

756
01:12:22.040 --> 01:12:26.240
<i>David. it's Elijah. It was so obvious.</i>

757
01:12:26.320 --> 01:12:28.840
<i>It was this one issue</i>
<i>that brought it back for me.</i>

758
01:12:28.920 --> 01:12:31.000
<i>Century Comics 117.</i>

759
01:12:31.120 --> 01:12:32.960
<i>That's where this group.</i>
<i>the Coalition of Evil.</i>

760
01:12:33.040 --> 01:12:35.800
<i>tried to ascertain the weakness</i>
<i>of every superhero.</i>

761
01:12:35.880 --> 01:12:39.360
<i>because they all have one.</i>
<i>just like you.</i>

762
01:12:39.440 --> 01:12:42.800
<i>Your bones don't break. mine do.</i>
<i>That's clear.</i>

763
01:12:43.520 --> 01:12:46.720
<i>Your cells react to bacteria</i>
<i>and viruses differently than mine.</i>

764
01:12:46.960 --> 01:12:50.760
<i>You don't get sick. I do.</i>
<i>That's also clear.</i>

765
01:12:51.040 --> 01:12:55.920
<i>But for some reason. you and I</i>
<i>react the exact same way to water.</i>

766
01:12:56.560 --> 01:13:00.160
<i>We swallow it too fast. we choke.</i>
<i>and we get some in our lungs.</i>

767
01:13:00.240 --> 01:13:01.640
<i>we drown.</i>

768
01:13:01.720 --> 01:13:05.840
<i>However unreal it may seem.</i>
<i>we are connected. you and I.</i>

769
01:13:06.600 --> 01:13:10.280
<i>We are on the same curve.</i>
<i>just on opposite ends.</i>

770
01:13:11.280 --> 01:13:14.360
<i>The point of all this</i>
<i>is we now know something we didn't.</i>

771
01:13:15.440 --> 01:13:18.560
<i>You have a weakness. Water.</i>

772
01:13:19.200 --> 01:13:20.720
<i>It's like your Kryptonite.</i>

773
01:13:22.080 --> 01:13:23.960
<i>You hearing me. David?</i>

774
01:15:14.280 --> 01:15:16.960
(DAVID PANTING)

775
01:15:39.040 --> 01:15:40.280
DAVID: Audrey?

776
01:16:06.640 --> 01:16:08.040
(GRUNTS)

777
01:16:14.320 --> 01:16:16.320
I gotcha. I gotcha.

778
01:16:34.720 --> 01:16:37.360
Audrey. Audrey?

779
01:16:37.440 --> 01:16:39.520
(CAR APPROACHING)

780
01:16:43.600 --> 01:16:45.040
Hey!

781
01:16:55.600 --> 01:16:59.800
My... I thought I was dead.

782
01:17:00.320 --> 01:17:03.040
Me. too. Me. too.

783
01:17:06.800 --> 01:17:08.280
Is she all right?

784
01:17:08.680 --> 01:17:10.400
I think her leg's broken.

785
01:17:11.240 --> 01:17:12.280
MAN: Are you hurt?

786
01:17:13.840 --> 01:17:15.280
Hey. man. are you hurt?

787
01:17:32.480 --> 01:17:33.840
(PHONE RINGING)

788
01:17:46.640 --> 01:17:47.840
Hello?

789
01:17:48.840 --> 01:17:50.920
<i>DAVID: I wasn't injured</i>
<i>in that car accident.</i>

790
01:17:51.640 --> 01:17:53.080
David.

791
01:17:54.160 --> 01:17:56.040
<i>I've never been injured. Elijah.</i>

792
01:17:59.080 --> 01:18:01.280
<i>What am I supposed to do?</i>

793
01:18:07.520 --> 01:18:09.520
Go to where people are.

794
01:18:10.320 --> 01:18:13.440
<i>ELIJAH: You won't have to</i>
<i>look very long.</i>

795
01:18:15.080 --> 01:18:17.600
<i>It's all right to be afraid. David.</i>

796
01:18:18.120 --> 01:18:20.600
<i>because this part won't be</i>
<i>like a comic book.</i>

797
01:18:22.120 --> 01:18:25.960
<i>Real life doesn't fit into little boxes</i>
<i>that were drawn for it.</i>

798
01:19:44.320 --> 01:19:45.360
(GLASS SHATTERING)

799
01:19:45.440 --> 01:19:47.400
Go back to Africa!

800
01:20:03.960 --> 01:20:06.440
Hey. what's your name?

801
01:20:08.080 --> 01:20:09.120
WOMAN: Huh?

802
01:20:11.920 --> 01:20:15.080
I think you drank too much.

803
01:20:59.640 --> 01:21:00.680
Can I come in?

804
01:21:01.680 --> 01:21:03.040
Who are you?

805
01:21:04.440 --> 01:21:06.160
I like your house.

806
01:21:07.280 --> 01:21:09.040
Can I come in?

807
01:21:09.280 --> 01:21:11.280
What is this?

808
01:21:13.200 --> 01:21:15.680
No. you can't come in.

809
01:21:16.720 --> 01:21:17.760
Are you sure?

810
01:21:19.000 --> 01:21:20.400
What are... What are you...

811
01:23:51.680 --> 01:23:54.120
<i>(CHATTERING ON TV)</i>

812
01:23:57.240 --> 01:23:58.280
(CLATTERING)

813
01:24:21.480 --> 01:24:23.400
<i>COMMENTATOR ON TV: Johnston</i>
<i>with his head against the fence.</i>

814
01:24:23.480 --> 01:24:27.240
<i>He's vulnerable because he doesn't</i>
<i>have the space to move as fast now.</i>

815
01:24:27.320 --> 01:24:29.200
<i>So he always stays in range.</i>

816
01:24:31.840 --> 01:24:35.000
<i>Johnston being warned</i>
<i>by referee John McCartney to move.</i>

817
01:24:35.440 --> 01:24:38.440
<i>Not an easy task right now.</i>

818
01:24:39.920 --> 01:24:42.080
<i>Shamrock's right hand</i>
<i>is his best hand.</i>

819
01:24:45.160 --> 01:24:47.880
<i>Right hand by Shamrock again.</i>
<i>Another one!</i>

820
01:24:48.000 --> 01:24:49.720
<i>Shamrock landing again!</i>

821
01:24:51.680 --> 01:24:53.280
(CLATTERING)

822
01:24:53.560 --> 01:24:54.600
<i>You want to win it.</i>

823
01:25:26.040 --> 01:25:29.600
(GIRL CRYING SOFTLY)

824
01:25:51.240 --> 01:25:53.400
It's okay.

825
01:25:56.120 --> 01:25:57.480
Come on.

826
01:25:59.680 --> 01:26:01.760
(CHILDREN CRYING)

827
01:26:03.760 --> 01:26:05.280
Okay. Come on.

828
01:26:17.880 --> 01:26:20.080
(SHUSHING)

829
01:27:35.240 --> 01:27:36.280
(COUGHING)

830
01:30:45.760 --> 01:30:46.800
(DAVID GRUNTS)

831
01:32:49.760 --> 01:32:52.200
I had a bad dream.

832
01:32:58.160 --> 01:32:59.880
It's over now.

833
01:33:14.800 --> 01:33:16.480
DAVID: (SOFTLY)
That's what I thought.

834
01:33:19.400 --> 01:33:22.000
AUDREY: (SOFTLY)
What were you thinking?

835
01:33:22.880 --> 01:33:23.920
DAVID: Well...

836
01:33:27.080 --> 01:33:28.360
AUDREY: It's me.

837
01:33:28.600 --> 01:33:29.920
DAVID: I don't know.

838
01:33:31.240 --> 01:33:32.920
I can't believe you'd think that.

839
01:33:33.280 --> 01:33:35.400
I'm just asking you.

840
01:33:38.560 --> 01:33:40.240
I'm making French toast.

841
01:33:56.240 --> 01:33:59.080
AUDREY: I've been thinking
about Elijah Price.

842
01:34:00.360 --> 01:34:03.280
If he shows up again. I think
we should call the police. okay?

843
01:34:07.880 --> 01:34:08.960
Okay?

844
01:34:12.560 --> 01:34:13.760
Okay.

845
01:35:22.480 --> 01:35:24.240
(WHISPERS) You were right.

846
01:35:51.720 --> 01:35:53.080
(CLASSICAL MUSIC PLAYING)

847
01:36:14.360 --> 01:36:17.440
This is one of Johann Davis'
earliest drawings.

848
01:36:18.560 --> 01:36:20.320
See the villain's eyes?

849
01:36:21.160 --> 01:36:23.080
They're larger
than the other characters'.

850
01:36:23.320 --> 01:36:28.640
They insinuate a slightly skewed
perspective on how they see the world.

851
01:36:30.000 --> 01:36:31.680
Just off normal.

852
01:36:32.400 --> 01:36:34.080
He doesn't look scary.

853
01:36:34.680 --> 01:36:36.880
That's what I said to my son.

854
01:36:37.440 --> 01:36:40.080
But he says there's always two kinds.

855
01:36:40.200 --> 01:36:44.080
There's the soldier villain
who fights the hero with his hands.

856
01:36:44.600 --> 01:36:46.640
and then there's the real threat.

857
01:36:46.720 --> 01:36:51.000
the brilliant and evil archenemy
who fights the hero with his mind.

858
01:36:51.760 --> 01:36:53.400
Are you Elijah's mother?

859
01:36:53.480 --> 01:36:56.160
I am. I'm helping him with the sale.

860
01:36:57.600 --> 01:37:00.120
Nice to meet you. I'm David Dunn.

861
01:37:00.400 --> 01:37:04.040
He's spoken of you.
Says you're becoming friends.

862
01:37:04.520 --> 01:37:05.840
We are.

863
01:37:07.120 --> 01:37:09.440
Looks like he's doing good today.

864
01:37:10.320 --> 01:37:12.680
I'm very proud of him.

865
01:37:13.400 --> 01:37:15.440
He's come through a lot in his life.

866
01:37:16.640 --> 01:37:19.760
Couple of bad spells
I thought had broken him.

867
01:37:21.600 --> 01:37:25.360
They were bad. But he made it.

868
01:37:27.040 --> 01:37:28.800
Yes. he did.

869
01:37:30.160 --> 01:37:32.320
He's kind of a miracle.

870
01:37:34.480 --> 01:37:35.520
Yes. he is.

871
01:37:40.320 --> 01:37:43.120
-I'll tell him you're here.
-Thank you.

872
01:38:13.000 --> 01:38:14.600
It has begun.

873
01:38:18.000 --> 01:38:20.160
Tell me something. David.

874
01:38:21.200 --> 01:38:24.800
When you woke up this morning.
was it still there?

875
01:38:25.720 --> 01:38:27.160
The sadness?

876
01:38:28.960 --> 01:38:30.040
DAVID: No.

877
01:38:34.640 --> 01:38:36.880
I think this is where we shake hands.

878
01:38:53.280 --> 01:38:54.640
(EXPLOSION)

879
01:38:54.880 --> 01:38:56.960
(ALL CLAMOURING)

880
01:39:01.920 --> 01:39:03.280
(POLICE SIREN WAILING)

881
01:39:04.800 --> 01:39:06.800
(ALARM RINGING)

882
01:39:08.920 --> 01:39:13.400
I worked in that building 25 years.
I know all its secrets.

883
01:39:15.040 --> 01:39:16.080
Secrets?

884
01:39:18.360 --> 01:39:22.840
Like. if there ever was a fire
on floors one. two or three.

885
01:39:23.680 --> 01:39:26.640
everyone in that hotel
would be burnt alive.

886
01:39:33.200 --> 01:39:35.280
MAN: Passengers aren't
allowed in there.

887
01:40:19.160 --> 01:40:22.400
ELIJAH: Do you know
what the scariest thing is?

888
01:40:25.400 --> 01:40:27.240
To not know your place in this world.

889
01:40:28.680 --> 01:40:30.960
To not know why you're here.

890
01:40:32.520 --> 01:40:38.040
That's... That's just an awful feeling.

891
01:40:40.120 --> 01:40:41.920
What have you done?

892
01:40:43.440 --> 01:40:45.640
I almost gave up hope.

893
01:40:47.120 --> 01:40:49.840
There were so many times
I questioned myself.

894
01:40:49.920 --> 01:40:52.360
You killed all those people.

895
01:40:53.640 --> 01:40:55.720
But I found you.

896
01:40:56.760 --> 01:41:02.880
So many sacrifices just to find you.

897
01:41:03.320 --> 01:41:04.640
Jesus Christ.

898
01:41:15.080 --> 01:41:16.960
Now that we know who you are.

899
01:41:19.120 --> 01:41:20.840
I know who I am.

900
01:41:25.320 --> 01:41:27.080
I'm not a mistake.

901
01:41:28.920 --> 01:41:30.920
ELIJAH: It all makes sense.

902
01:41:31.560 --> 01:41:35.160
In a comic. you know how you can tell
who the archvillain's going to be?

903
01:41:36.080 --> 01:41:39.240
He's the exact opposite of the hero.

904
01:41:39.480 --> 01:41:42.440
And most times they're friends.
like you and me.

905
01:41:43.160 --> 01:41:46.800
I should've known way back when.
You know why. David?

906
01:41:47.080 --> 01:41:48.720
Because of the kids.

907
01:41:59.360 --> 01:42:01.480
They called me Mr Glass.

